00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:26.770
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: In
some ways, today's class,

00:00:26.770 --> 00:00:30.150
it's the most challenging
of the semester.

00:00:30.150 --> 00:00:34.770
These are really complicated,
difficult threshold issues.

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:38.970
And we're just starting to
see the powerful ramifications

00:00:38.970 --> 00:00:41.760
of having gotten a number of
things wrong in this space

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:44.070
and what it does.

00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:46.890
So I try to put
the manufacturing

00:00:46.890 --> 00:00:51.390
stuff in early so you'd see
that there are real issues here,

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:55.380
not just kind of abstract
science policy questions,

00:00:55.380 --> 00:00:58.770
but real issues that
have big implications.

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:09.480
So let me start with Samuelson.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:16.820
And you're all probably
familiar with him,

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:21.230
but probably among a handful
of the most famous economists

00:01:21.230 --> 00:01:22.530
of the 20th century--

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:26.960
one of MIT'S great
stars, an amazing figure,

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:30.800
lived well into his 90s.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:36.450
I heard him talk just a few
years ago, before he died.

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:41.400
And he was incredibly sharp
and funny and astute--

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:43.020
just a phenomenal figure.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:46.710
And he really rethought--

00:01:46.710 --> 00:01:48.900
really was a
foundational creator

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:51.090
of neoclassical
economics-- the attempt

00:01:51.090 --> 00:01:56.250
to bring discipline metrics
to economic thinking.

00:01:56.250 --> 00:02:01.170
So then he writes
this surprising piece

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:06.340
in 2004, which takes on
mainstream economics.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.780
Now, he had actually done
writing on this topic,

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:11.400
coming to somewhat
similar conclusions

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:13.560
much, much earlier
in his career.

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:16.590
But he comes back
to it in this piece.

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:20.310
And it took everybody
aback, right.

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:22.110
Mainstream economics
had thought this was

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:25.500
a completely settled territory.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.750
Mainstream economists
like Greenspan,

00:02:27.750 --> 00:02:34.890
Jagdish Bhagwati, Gregory
Mankiw, they were arguing--

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:36.870
and this is a
quote from Mankiw--

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:39.720
"Yes, good jobs may be
lost in the short run,

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.260
but still total US net
national product must,

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:45.480
by economic laws of
comparative advantage,

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:47.670
be raised in the long run--

00:02:47.670 --> 00:02:48.990
and in China, too.

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:52.980
Never forget the real gains of
consumers alongside admitted

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:56.940
possible losses of some
producers in this working out

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:58.920
of what Schumpeter called
'creative capitalist

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:00.060
destruction.'

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:03.390
Correct economic law recognizes
that some American groups can

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:05.610
be hurt by dynamic free trade.

00:03:05.610 --> 00:03:08.100
But correct economic
law vindicates the word

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:10.680
'creative' destruction
by its proof

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:12.870
that the gains of
the American winners

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:17.010
are big enough to more than
compensate for the losers."

00:03:17.010 --> 00:03:21.120
And then Samuelson concludes,
"The last paragraph can only

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:24.240
be in innuendo, for
it is dead wrong

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:27.990
about the necessary supply
of winnings over losings."

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:34.260
So here is the guy who created
mainstream economics taking

00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:38.640
on the whole economic mainstream
assumption about the benefits

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:40.650
and gains of trade.

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:42.480
And it's a startling moment.

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:47.580
This article was like
a bombshell in 2004.

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:53.460
So how could the US be a loser
in competition with a low wage,

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:55.690
lower cost competitor
like China-- obviously,

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:57.000
there's others--

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.240
despite David Ricardo's theory
of comparative advantage?

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:03.990
And remember, we talked
in the first class

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:06.480
about Ricardo's theory
of comparative advantage.

00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:09.600
We had the example of
Portugal and England.

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:11.850
England gets a lot of rain,
and it has a lot of grass.

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:12.475
It grows sheep.

00:04:12.475 --> 00:04:14.790
Portugal has a lot more
sun and a lot less rain.

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:15.990
It grows grapes.

00:04:15.990 --> 00:04:20.010
It produces wine and port.

00:04:20.010 --> 00:04:22.800
Each side trades to their
comparative advantage.

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:27.480
Now, he's thinking of a
resource advantage, right.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:30.810
He's not thinking about
a comparative innovation

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:32.020
advantage.

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:37.410
So what happens in the time
from Ricardo to the present,

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:41.520
is that nations begin building
a comparative innovation

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:44.830
advantage through building
strong innovation systems,

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:45.720
right.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.920
And arguably, the US leads
that effort, coming out

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:52.890
of World War II to develop
a comparative innovation

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:53.780
advantage.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:02.510
And Samuelson goes on
to argue that if China

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:04.610
or another comparable
country begins

00:05:04.610 --> 00:05:07.580
to make productivity-enhancing
gains in its production

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:10.160
and couples that with
a wage advantage,

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:13.310
it can capture some of the
comparative advantage that

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:16.580
had belonged to a
competitor like the US.

00:05:16.580 --> 00:05:22.920
So in a Ricardo sense,
there's never unemployment

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:24.740
that lasts forever from trade.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:27.870
It will eventually
sort itself out, right.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:30.810
But the way in which it's
been sorting itself out

00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:33.300
is that, as he
puts it, real wages

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:38.200
have been lowered by this
version of dynamic fair trade.

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:44.760
So to compete, wages come
down, right, in the US.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:48.600
And that's what's been going on.

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:52.530
So wages can drop
after a time to a point

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:55.920
where a productivity enhancement
or productivity advantage

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:59.970
in another country is offset.

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:04.560
But these are still net
harmful terms of trade.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:10.210
And this is not a
new story, right.

00:06:10.210 --> 00:06:12.930
This story has been going on for
a long time, Samuelson argues.

00:06:12.930 --> 00:06:15.690
So farming moves from the
eastern part of the United

00:06:15.690 --> 00:06:18.150
States to the Midwest.

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:21.420
That's a straight
comparative advantage--

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:23.670
the ability to scale up
agricultural production

00:06:23.670 --> 00:06:28.330
in the Midwest, as opposed
to the more crowded East

00:06:28.330 --> 00:06:31.050
and hillier East
and rockier East.

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:31.710
We can see it.

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:35.070
We understand why
agricultural production

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:36.750
shifts to the Midwest.

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:39.960
Textile and shoe manufacturing
moved from New England

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:44.220
to the lower wage South
early at the beginning

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:45.930
of the 20th century.

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:50.490
English manufacturing
leadership shifts to the US,

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:53.130
starting in the middle of
the 19th century, right.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:57.130
We develop the early
stages of mass production

00:06:57.130 --> 00:06:59.130
through interchangeable,
machine-made parts, not

00:06:59.130 --> 00:06:59.630
Britain.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:02.190
And we'll talk more about
that in a later class.

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:04.800
So as Samuelson
puts it, even where

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:07.530
the leaders continue to
progress in absolute growth,

00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:11.160
their rate of growth
tended to be attenuated

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:14.190
by an adverse headwind
generated from lower wage

00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:16.680
competitors and other
technical imitators

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:18.160
in each one of these examples.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:21.240
Right, so this is an
old economic story

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:23.490
that he's raising.

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:26.250
So a productivity
gain in one country

00:07:26.250 --> 00:07:29.070
can benefit that country alone,
while permanently hurting

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:31.920
the other country by
reducing the gains

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.220
from trade that are possible
between the two countries.

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:36.600
And all of this,
he acknowledges,

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:42.720
is long-run
Schumpeterian effects--

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.570
creative destruction
of capitalism effects.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:49.080
And he concludes that in effect
is a roulette wheel of evolving

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:51.000
comparative advantage.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.690
Now his warning
is a powerful one.

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:58.680
If you respond with
tariffs and protectionism,

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:03.335
you will be breeding
economic arterial sclerosis.

00:08:03.335 --> 00:08:04.710
You will be limiting
your ability

00:08:04.710 --> 00:08:07.260
to effectively and
efficiently compete.

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:11.520
So that's not a fix in his mind.

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:17.610
So this is one of the
most important economists

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:21.540
of the last century,
and a good part of this,

00:08:21.540 --> 00:08:26.220
weighing in on an
historic conclusion

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:29.820
that economics came to about
the overall benefits of trade,

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:33.919
and saying it's a much more
complicated story than that.

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:39.059
So it was a powerful message
when he put this out.

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:42.840
So I just finished
talking about Samuelson.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:48.180
So we're all set up for you to
do us your view of Samuelson

00:08:48.180 --> 00:08:49.990
and lead us into some Q&A.

