00:27:12.635 --> 00:27:13.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:14.060 --> 00:27:14.795
Right.

00:27:14.795 --> 00:27:16.670
This class is designed
to scare you to death.

00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:17.253
AUDIENCE: Yup.

00:27:17.253 --> 00:27:18.094
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:18.594 --> 00:27:21.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
I find that isn't it

00:27:21.480 --> 00:27:23.606
counter-intuitive for
the US to train so much

00:27:23.606 --> 00:27:26.843
international students, and
knowing that most of them

00:27:26.843 --> 00:27:28.586
will return to
their home country

00:27:28.586 --> 00:27:30.675
and contribute to the
industry commons over there?

00:27:30.675 --> 00:27:31.545
AUDIENCE: Well, see,
that's fascinating,

00:27:31.545 --> 00:27:33.655
because I heard the
assumption actually

00:27:33.655 --> 00:27:36.025
be that the US keeps the
international students,

00:27:36.025 --> 00:27:37.370
and that's why.

00:27:37.370 --> 00:27:40.296
I mean, we've mentioned it
in several classes, right?

00:27:40.296 --> 00:27:42.195
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE], right?

00:27:42.195 --> 00:27:44.023
AUDIENCE: They might still do.

00:27:44.023 --> 00:27:46.190
AUDIENCE: Probably true,
but maybe at a lesser rate.

00:27:46.190 --> 00:27:48.800
Because I think the
opportunities available now

00:27:48.800 --> 00:27:51.590
in the US manufacturing sector,
just like outside the US--

00:27:51.590 --> 00:27:54.470
for people that come
here and do train,

00:27:54.470 --> 00:27:56.810
it's now a lot more
feasible for me to go back,

00:27:56.810 --> 00:27:58.770
whereas previously I
would have had to stay.

00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:01.522
And so we're seeing sort of
a decreasing rate [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:01.522 --> 00:28:02.022
to stay.

00:28:02.022 --> 00:28:02.674
AUDIENCE: More desirable
to stay, right?

00:28:02.674 --> 00:28:05.114
It's like the common
example we've used in class,

00:28:05.114 --> 00:28:06.578
I think maybe two
or three times,

00:28:06.578 --> 00:28:09.018
is that with every diploma
and cap received in the US,

00:28:09.018 --> 00:28:11.713
we should staple a visa.

00:28:11.713 --> 00:28:13.880
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Heck,
let's staple a green card.

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:14.857
To heck with the visa.

00:28:14.857 --> 00:28:15.095
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:15.095 --> 00:28:16.045
AUDIENCE: A green card, sorry.

00:28:16.045 --> 00:28:16.837
That's what I mean.

00:28:16.837 --> 00:28:19.528
But yeah, so what
does the data actually

00:28:19.528 --> 00:28:20.912
look like on that bill?

00:28:20.912 --> 00:28:22.870
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Well,
a significant portion

00:28:22.870 --> 00:28:25.840
of students from abroad
do stay here, right.

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:27.620
But the numbers are in decline.

00:28:27.620 --> 00:28:29.620
And more are going back
to their home countries.

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:32.050
But does that mean--
you all tell me--

00:28:32.050 --> 00:28:33.550
that the US ought
to close its doors

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:34.725
to international students?

00:28:34.725 --> 00:28:36.100
Right, is that
what we should do?

00:28:36.100 --> 00:28:38.980
Right, is that the
right economic strategy?

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:42.613
We've got somebody who
thinks it is, at the moment.

00:28:42.613 --> 00:28:45.030
AUDIENCE: You know yesterday
he passed another one, right?

00:28:45.030 --> 00:28:45.640
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Yeah, I know.

00:28:45.640 --> 00:28:46.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:47.310 --> 00:28:48.110
No.

00:28:48.110 --> 00:28:51.490
No, really-- I'm asking
in a serious kind of way.

00:28:51.490 --> 00:28:53.590
I mean, the US
model, historically,

00:28:53.590 --> 00:28:55.668
was to have these
international universities

00:28:55.668 --> 00:28:57.460
and attract talent from
all over the place.

00:28:57.460 --> 00:29:00.550
Because if you're running
an innovation system

00:29:00.550 --> 00:29:03.310
that feeds talent for
the entire world, what

00:29:03.310 --> 00:29:05.680
an incredible competitive
advantage, right?

00:29:05.680 --> 00:29:08.015
What an incredible
competitive opportunity.

00:29:08.015 --> 00:29:09.640
But I think the other
side of that coin

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:13.430
is that it's a value in itself.

00:29:13.430 --> 00:29:17.350
And yeah, you really asked
some terrific questions

00:29:17.350 --> 00:29:18.480
in your email to me.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:21.550
And this is one of them.

00:29:21.550 --> 00:29:22.880
What are these Americans doing?

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:23.380
Right.

00:29:23.380 --> 00:29:26.290
What do they think
they're doing here?

00:29:26.290 --> 00:29:28.720
But I still think
it's of overall value

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:31.570
to have as much talent here,
because that's how knowledge

00:29:31.570 --> 00:29:33.670
gets sharpened, right.

00:29:33.670 --> 00:29:35.440
That's how we get
sharper and better.

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:38.170
And so that would
be my argument.

00:29:38.170 --> 00:29:40.780
But people should
feel free to disagree.

00:29:40.780 --> 00:29:44.900
AUDIENCE: So in a way that--

00:29:44.900 --> 00:29:46.910
I feel really uncomfortable
when people say,

00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:48.478
I want to play the
devil's advocate.

00:29:48.478 --> 00:29:51.020
Because I feel like those people
are trying to be incendiary.

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:53.360
But I certainly have had
peers in the past that

00:29:53.360 --> 00:29:56.060
would have raised the
point of this conversation

00:29:56.060 --> 00:29:58.970
about whether students who are
coming from other countries

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:01.250
might be considered
spies, because they

00:30:01.250 --> 00:30:05.840
would be then understanding
knowledge and the innovation

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:07.910
or sort of innovation
paradigm, and then

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:10.010
taking it back to
their home countries.

00:30:10.010 --> 00:30:12.440
And that also makes
me feel uncomfortable,

00:30:12.440 --> 00:30:16.430
because I feel like trust
sort of precludes cooperation.

00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:19.310
And it precludes the
United States' ability

00:30:19.310 --> 00:30:20.695
to work in a globalized system.

00:30:20.695 --> 00:30:22.987
So I was hoping that you
could talk about that a little

00:30:22.987 --> 00:30:23.487
as well.

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:33.290
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: In the
end, having a world talent base

00:30:33.290 --> 00:30:36.563
with common education
experiences--

00:30:36.563 --> 00:30:38.480
that's very powerful for
the world in general.

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:41.390
I mean, that's a
real huge net plus.

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:45.350
And we can't assume
that all innovation is

00:30:45.350 --> 00:30:46.850
going to happen in
the United States

00:30:46.850 --> 00:30:48.140
and we can wall ourselves off.

00:30:48.140 --> 00:30:50.465
It's important for innovation
to occur elsewhere.

00:30:53.360 --> 00:31:01.320
There's an old story about
small towns and lawyers, right.

00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:07.871
So if there's a small town
and there's one lawyer,

00:31:07.871 --> 00:31:09.946
the lawyer is going to starve.

00:31:09.946 --> 00:31:12.940
If there's a small
town and two lawyers,

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:15.173
they're both going
to get rich, right.

00:31:15.173 --> 00:31:17.590
Because their clients will be
suing each other constantly,

00:31:17.590 --> 00:31:18.090
right.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:21.370
In other words, they're going
to create more net, right.

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:25.210
And if China is doing
brilliant things

00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:29.920
to bring 300, 400 or
more million people

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:33.040
into its middle class, that's
a great thing for the world.

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:36.180
That's a great, overall
incredible net plus,

00:31:36.180 --> 00:31:40.060
to create a massive
new middle class.

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:42.880
And if the US can't figure out
how to take advantage of that,

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:45.670
then shame on us, right.

00:31:45.670 --> 00:31:48.490
Because it's really important
that the world do these things,

00:31:48.490 --> 00:31:49.120
right.

00:31:49.120 --> 00:31:50.140
Same story in India.

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:52.390
Same story and all kinds of
other developing countries

00:31:52.390 --> 00:31:54.470
that are starting to
become emerging economies.

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:56.660
So these things need to happen.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:32:00.610
And we're not going to
be able to wall them off.

00:32:00.610 --> 00:32:02.560
We just have to figure out--

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:04.480
to develop our own
competitive capabilities

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:06.075
to be participating.

00:32:06.075 --> 00:32:07.450
That would be what
I would argue.

00:32:07.450 --> 00:32:10.130
Now, a lot of people
see this differently.

00:32:10.130 --> 00:32:10.630
Matthew?

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:12.089
AUDIENCE: I think
another benefit--

00:32:12.089 --> 00:32:15.004
even if you didn't care about
the Chinese middle class

00:32:15.004 --> 00:32:18.880
or India's middle class, and
if you just cared about the US,

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:20.880
you'd still have to
recognize that we don't have

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:22.530
the comparative
advantage in everything

00:32:22.530 --> 00:32:24.250
such as advanced manufacturing.

00:32:24.250 --> 00:32:26.210
By having those
international students there,

00:32:26.210 --> 00:32:29.750
like say, a Sloan
student who was working

00:32:29.750 --> 00:32:31.530
in manufacturing in China--

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:33.360
just as much as they're
maybe benefiting

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:36.690
from the US education and
that innovation mindset,

00:32:36.690 --> 00:32:39.195
they're sharing with their
peers their experiences.

00:32:39.195 --> 00:32:39.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:40.862
I think that's important.

00:32:40.862 --> 00:32:43.330
And when we consider
the educational model

00:32:43.330 --> 00:32:46.060
and bringing international
people into that,

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:48.850
I think it's important to
not adopt the perspective

00:32:48.850 --> 00:32:51.430
that we're the only ones
who have anything to offer.

00:32:51.430 --> 00:32:52.880
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: You got it.

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:54.880
AUDIENCE: Other people
bring other perspectives.

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:55.963
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

00:32:55.963 --> 00:32:58.390
AUDIENCE: And that's valuable
even just for our benefit,

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:01.860
not to mention other countries'
benefit, which is good.

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:05.160
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So, Luyao
have we answered your question?

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:05.783
Yeah?

00:33:05.783 --> 00:33:07.950
Are you satisfied with what
we've talked about here?

00:33:07.950 --> 00:33:08.783
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLES]

00:33:08.783 --> 00:33:11.283
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
You can critique us.

00:33:11.283 --> 00:33:14.040
AUDIENCE: Well,
personally I think

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:17.080
it, just for the
sake of the world,

00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:21.180
is benefiting to have an
international base of talents.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:22.950
And there are
countries that see this

00:33:22.950 --> 00:33:27.505
as a national strategic
move, to attract talents,

00:33:27.505 --> 00:33:28.720
like Singapore.

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:31.780
But because they are such a
small country and their only

00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:34.482
resources-- the human talents--

00:33:34.482 --> 00:33:38.242
then I don't know if the
US sees this as something

00:33:38.242 --> 00:33:40.220
of national importance.

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:41.660
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Right.

00:33:41.660 --> 00:33:43.700
Your Singapore example
is very astute.

00:33:43.700 --> 00:33:44.700
It's really interesting.

00:33:44.700 --> 00:33:48.120
Because Singapore, at least
until fairly recently,

00:33:48.120 --> 00:33:50.520
had a strategy for
higher education,

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:52.500
in particular
graduate education,

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:55.020
to get its students out
into the world, right--

00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.240
to send them to the best
educational institutions

00:33:57.240 --> 00:34:00.660
around the world, so that they
would learn other countries

00:34:00.660 --> 00:34:02.760
and how they worked
and what ideas

00:34:02.760 --> 00:34:05.435
could be gained from them--

00:34:05.435 --> 00:34:07.560
and that they would be able
to set up relationships

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:08.510
with those countries.

00:34:08.510 --> 00:34:10.510
They would be able to
have working relationships

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:13.500
with the communities
that they learned.

00:34:13.500 --> 00:34:20.670
And Singapore--
small island nation--

00:34:20.670 --> 00:34:24.870
city-state, really--
no real resources.

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:26.820
They have to trade to live.

00:34:26.820 --> 00:34:31.199
So they organize themselves
around becoming intermediaries

00:34:31.199 --> 00:34:34.380
in all kinds of
trading activities

00:34:34.380 --> 00:34:36.900
worldwide, whether
it's petroleum

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:40.260
and oil and fossil
fuels, or it's

00:34:40.260 --> 00:34:43.500
running the world's
most efficient port

00:34:43.500 --> 00:34:49.093
or running the most efficient
cargo transport aircraft

00:34:49.093 --> 00:34:50.760
operation in the
world, they figured out

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:52.320
these intermediary spots.

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:54.808
And then they used their
relationship building

00:34:54.808 --> 00:34:56.850
to be able to build the
relationships they needed

00:34:56.850 --> 00:34:59.670
to play that dramatic
intermediary role benefited

00:34:59.670 --> 00:35:01.140
by their geography.

00:35:01.140 --> 00:35:04.200
So it's a very interesting
example, Luyao,

00:35:04.200 --> 00:35:09.120
of a country that's adopted kind
of a broad look at education

00:35:09.120 --> 00:35:11.136
and where to get it.

00:35:11.136 --> 00:35:12.780
AUDIENCE: And to
add on to that--

00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:13.066
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Please.

00:35:13.066 --> 00:35:15.690
AUDIENCE: --with that kind of
strategy, there are, of course,

00:35:15.690 --> 00:35:17.280
social costs.

00:35:17.280 --> 00:35:23.030
There are like local hatreds
of international laborers.

00:35:23.030 --> 00:35:26.840
And the government
takes a responsibility

00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:30.900
to settle this conflict
instead of reducing

00:35:30.900 --> 00:35:33.080
international
talents, because they

00:35:33.080 --> 00:35:35.440
see this as a strategic move.

00:35:35.440 --> 00:35:40.640
And so it is the question,
like, when we see maybe

00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:44.580
there is an outsourcing
of manufacturing,

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:49.120
there are loss of talents.

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:52.735
Or do we just stop doing it?

00:35:52.735 --> 00:35:55.090
Or should the government
take the responsibility

00:35:55.090 --> 00:35:58.240
to solve the social
costs associated

00:35:58.240 --> 00:36:03.982
with this kind of move,
together with globalization?

00:36:03.982 --> 00:36:05.920
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Have at it, team.

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:07.975
What do you think?

00:36:07.975 --> 00:36:09.600
AUDIENCE: So on the
point of education,

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:12.560
higher education, that's one of
the US's important abilities.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:15.210
So it's a really good thing.

00:36:15.210 --> 00:36:16.710
It's dangerous to
assume that that's

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:19.015
going to be a core strength
for a long period of time.

00:36:19.015 --> 00:36:22.150
So people will learn
from us and [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:24.580
There's a couple good
universities popping up

00:36:24.580 --> 00:36:26.957
in other countries
that are doing well.

00:36:26.957 --> 00:36:29.290
I think the big danger, though,
is the point [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:29.290 --> 00:36:34.030
made previously about why should
[INAUDIBLE] create more value?

00:36:34.030 --> 00:36:37.260
Because ideas don't matter as
much as the execution of ideas.

00:36:37.260 --> 00:36:38.635
Like, there's a
ton of people who

00:36:38.635 --> 00:36:39.790
came up with social networks.

00:36:39.790 --> 00:36:41.582
Facebook had 15 social
networks beforehand.

00:36:41.582 --> 00:36:43.988
But it wasn't until one
person executed it right.

00:36:43.988 --> 00:36:46.030
So the danger is, we could
invent something here,

00:36:46.030 --> 00:36:48.860
and another company in
China has-- he's like,

00:36:48.860 --> 00:36:50.340
oh, that's a great idea.

00:36:50.340 --> 00:36:51.010
We can do that.

00:36:51.010 --> 00:36:51.843
We can do it better.

00:36:51.843 --> 00:36:53.240
And we can do it cheaper.

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:55.540
And that's the real kind of
thing I would worry about,

00:36:55.540 --> 00:36:57.770
is that capability of
being able to execute.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:37:01.380
And it's something
that's hard to understand

00:37:01.380 --> 00:37:04.430
until you've see it just
happen and gone through it.

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:06.262
But that's the danger.

00:37:06.262 --> 00:37:08.220
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So
Kevin, how about another

00:37:08.220 --> 00:37:14.633
question-- a closing question
on Gary Pisano and Willy Shih.

00:37:14.633 --> 00:37:16.525
AUDIENCE: Throughout
this whole discussion--

00:37:16.525 --> 00:37:18.672
this might be beyond
the scope of the class--

00:37:18.672 --> 00:37:20.505
there's a question that
popped into my head.

00:37:20.505 --> 00:37:22.890
If there stands to be
so much mutual benefit

00:37:22.890 --> 00:37:28.590
from global cooperation, why
don't countries prioritize it?

00:37:28.590 --> 00:37:31.140
That might be an
idealistic view.

00:37:31.140 --> 00:37:34.107
But if economies now are
so interconnected by trade

00:37:34.107 --> 00:37:38.550
and competition and everything,
why don't governments

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:43.810
of the world cooperate to
sort of prop each other up?

00:37:43.810 --> 00:37:45.685
And I'm as cynical as
the next person, right.

00:37:45.685 --> 00:37:50.130
I understand human greed and
the desire for money, right--

00:37:50.130 --> 00:37:51.900
desire to be the best.

00:37:51.900 --> 00:37:54.895
But why can't everyone
sort of be the best?

00:37:54.895 --> 00:37:56.270
AUDIENCE: That's
a good question.

00:37:56.270 --> 00:37:57.200
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:57.200 --> 00:37:58.130
AUDIENCE: [CHUCKLES]

00:37:58.130 --> 00:38:01.790
AUDIENCE: So often
the people who

00:38:01.790 --> 00:38:06.480
have to make these
decisions, they usually

00:38:06.480 --> 00:38:10.520
want to put their people first--
like, hey, America first.

00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:13.955
So that usually means
it's America first

00:38:13.955 --> 00:38:16.670
at the cost of anyone else.

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:20.450
So if you have 196
governments, all of which who

00:38:20.450 --> 00:38:22.990
are thinking like that,
then, well, you kind of

00:38:22.990 --> 00:38:24.970
end up where we are today.

00:38:24.970 --> 00:38:28.310
And it's short-term, yes.

00:38:28.310 --> 00:38:31.893
And I'll try to play a
bit of devil's advocate.

00:38:31.893 --> 00:38:33.060
I know you hate that, Lilly.

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:33.485
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:33.485 --> 00:38:34.335
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I hate it.

00:38:34.335 --> 00:38:35.270
AUDIENCE: I love it.

00:38:35.270 --> 00:38:37.757
Honestly, I love that phrase.

00:38:37.757 --> 00:38:39.340
AUDIENCE: As an
intellectual exercise,

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:40.150
I think it's important.

00:38:40.150 --> 00:38:40.730
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:38:40.730 --> 00:38:42.580
AUDIENCE: But if you do it
from not a place of trying

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:44.620
to find an understanding
with other people,

00:38:44.620 --> 00:38:47.590
then I think it
is irresponsible.

00:38:47.590 --> 00:38:48.870
AUDIENCE: So I see the--

00:38:52.983 --> 00:38:53.650
I lost my point.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:54.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:55.467 --> 00:38:57.050
AUDIENCE: Global
corporate [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:57.050 --> 00:38:58.720
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:58.720 --> 00:39:08.920
Yeah, so I see why long-term
it would be good to cooperate.

00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:12.350
But in the short-term,
if somebody, say,

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:15.140
reneges on a deal
when you've already

00:39:15.140 --> 00:39:17.240
put billions and billions
of dollars into it,

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:18.657
that could hurt
you significantly.

00:39:18.657 --> 00:39:20.455
And then they could
get away scot-free.

00:39:20.455 --> 00:39:21.830
And then they
could realize, hey,

00:39:21.830 --> 00:39:23.390
I've damaged this country that--

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:26.780
I don't know-- for
whatever reason,

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:32.030
I wanted to have less economic
benefit than what I'm getting.

00:39:32.030 --> 00:39:35.860
So basically, it comes
down to mistrust.

00:39:35.860 --> 00:39:37.660
So like that could happen.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:39.340
Yes, "we are the world."

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:40.840
I'd love for it to happen.

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:43.680
But I think it's going
to take a long time.

00:39:43.680 --> 00:39:46.253
AUDIENCE: So to point
out, we've definitely

00:39:46.253 --> 00:39:48.170
