00:39:48.170 --> 00:39:48.480
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:49.688
AUDIENCE: Colonialism exists.

00:39:49.688 --> 00:39:50.188
So--

00:39:50.188 --> 00:39:51.030
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHS]

00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:52.405
AUDIENCE: --we've
definitely gone

00:39:52.405 --> 00:39:54.810
to countries and different
places around the world,

00:39:54.810 --> 00:39:58.400
and really just
ravished for resources,

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:00.740
technological abilities,
what have you.

00:40:00.740 --> 00:40:03.175
And then, I think there's
a longstanding history

00:40:03.175 --> 00:40:07.640
of us kind of doing that and not
doing it right, just because it

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:11.015
is so advantageous for one
party to renege or do it wrong

00:40:11.015 --> 00:40:13.140
and go in for the wrong
reasons in the first place.

00:40:13.140 --> 00:40:15.710
And I think that
level of trust is

00:40:15.710 --> 00:40:17.450
sort of hard to build
from that history,

00:40:17.450 --> 00:40:19.710
but also, in the
case of [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:23.470
so let's say you build this
multi-national cooperation

00:40:23.470 --> 00:40:28.780
and somebody does sort
of renege on a deal,

00:40:28.780 --> 00:40:31.960
I can't see really
a conflict mediation

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:36.520
peace or a medium there that
doesn't escalate very quickly,

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:40.130
especially when large economic
threats are involved-- so maybe

00:40:40.130 --> 00:40:42.330
war or something.

00:40:42.330 --> 00:40:45.110
War is the extreme
example, but like tariffs--

00:40:45.110 --> 00:40:47.713
there could be large trade
implications that now--

00:40:47.713 --> 00:40:50.130
whereas previously they would
have been isolated to larger

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:51.963
countries, but now that
it's multi-national,

00:40:51.963 --> 00:40:53.650
it affects sort of everybody.

00:40:53.650 --> 00:40:56.317
AUDIENCE: I'm trying to think of
a memoir I was reading recently

00:40:56.317 --> 00:40:58.420
about a woman named
Wangari Maathai in Kenya

00:40:58.420 --> 00:41:02.390
about her experiences of growing
up right as British colonialism

00:41:02.390 --> 00:41:04.060
was taking off in the 1940s.

00:41:04.060 --> 00:41:07.550
And she was speaking of
the ways in which society

00:41:07.550 --> 00:41:09.940
had been structured
in her village

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:15.300
and that different ethnic
groups had become, I guess,

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:16.975
specialized in
certain capacities.

00:41:16.975 --> 00:41:19.100
Like, some people were very
