00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:53.680
And I think it's precisely what
this woman is talking about--

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:56.490
why cooperation is so difficult,
which is why I brought up game

00:41:56.490 --> 00:41:58.210
theory I think two classes ago--

00:41:58.210 --> 00:42:01.350
because cooperation and
collaboration are so important,

00:42:01.350 --> 00:42:04.420
but they rest so much a
sort of fundamental trust.

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:07.030
And that kind of
collaboration always

00:42:07.030 --> 00:42:08.890
sort of implies
a power imbalance

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:11.590
that is negated by
that sense of trust.

00:42:11.590 --> 00:42:14.230
And it's so difficult
on a global scale

00:42:14.230 --> 00:42:18.230
to enact trust and
collaboration because there

00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:20.650
is such a sense of
histories and colonialism

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:23.750
of power imbalances-- of
domination and hegemony.

00:42:23.750 --> 00:42:26.930
And because we have
been, for the past 200

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:30.050
years in the United States,
such strong actors in that,

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:33.530
we've never had to take this
into consideration before.

00:42:33.530 --> 00:42:34.910
And I think now, in particular--

00:42:34.910 --> 00:42:37.040
I really wish that
we had more students

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:38.630
in this course who
were sort of coming

00:42:38.630 --> 00:42:40.113
from defense backgrounds.

00:42:40.113 --> 00:42:41.780
Because I feel like
we don't talk enough

00:42:41.780 --> 00:42:45.930
about the implications of war or
the implications bioterrorism.

00:42:45.930 --> 00:42:47.930
But I do think it's
certainly important to think

00:42:47.930 --> 00:42:50.000
about collaboration
as our ideal.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.660
But as we were talking
