00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:32.350
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Interesting.

00:45:32.350 --> 00:45:33.250
All right.

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:40.090
We'll now dive into Jonas Nahm
and Ed Steinfeld, both of whom

00:45:40.090 --> 00:45:41.020
worked in MIT.

00:45:41.020 --> 00:45:45.205
So Jonas is now teaching
at Johns Hopkins SAIS.

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:51.340
And he's from Germany, fluent
Mandarin, spent lots and lots

00:45:51.340 --> 00:45:52.070
of time in China.

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:54.760
So he knows both German
and Chinese economics

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:57.070
and manufacturing
systems, in particular.

00:45:57.070 --> 00:46:02.140
Ed Steinfeld has gone on to head
the Watson Institute at Brown

00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:04.240
from MIT political
science department.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:09.040
Both are terrific
scholars of the kind

00:46:09.040 --> 00:46:11.260
of manufacturing
advances that China

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.110
has been able to put together.

00:46:14.110 --> 00:46:17.050
So this dramatic thing happens.

00:46:17.050 --> 00:46:21.833
China moves from 5.7% of global
manufacturing output in 2000

00:46:21.833 --> 00:46:27.100
to almost 20% in 2011,
passing the US in output.

00:46:27.100 --> 00:46:31.990
I mean, that is
startling, right.

00:46:31.990 --> 00:46:34.540
Those numbers jump off the page.

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:36.230
How did that happen?

00:46:36.230 --> 00:46:37.400
Right.

00:46:37.400 --> 00:46:39.480
So what happened here?

00:46:39.480 --> 00:46:42.260
So the operating
assumption in the US

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:46.640
has been that China
had lower production

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:51.320
costs due to lower wage
costs and lower cost parts.

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:53.480
That was the
operating assumption.

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:56.300
And then there's been
an assumption in the US

00:46:56.300 --> 00:46:59.650
that manufacturing naturally
migrates to low-cost producers

00:46:59.650 --> 00:47:02.390
and that the knowledge required
for manufacturing processes

00:47:02.390 --> 00:47:05.000
is comparatively trivial.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.813
And Nahm and Steinfeld argue,
neither of those is true.

00:47:09.813 --> 00:47:11.480
The assumption that
production knowledge

00:47:11.480 --> 00:47:15.155
flowed via multinationals
from outside into China--

00:47:15.155 --> 00:47:17.030
it's a much more
complicated story than that.

00:47:17.030 --> 00:47:20.690
The assumption that the IT
revolution enables severing

00:47:20.690 --> 00:47:22.670
of manufacturing from R&D--

00:47:22.670 --> 00:47:26.120
from production and design--

00:47:26.120 --> 00:47:30.260
and turns out to be a
more complicated story.

00:47:30.260 --> 00:47:36.230
And none of these explanations
explain that dramatic rise

00:47:36.230 --> 00:47:40.970
in China's production
capability and output.

00:47:40.970 --> 00:47:47.390
Instead, they argue
that China has developed

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:53.660
some remarkable new process
innovation and manufacturing

00:47:53.660 --> 00:47:54.410
innovation.

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:57.980
And that needs to be
understood and respected

00:47:57.980 --> 00:48:00.290
as a major innovation advance.

00:48:00.290 --> 00:48:06.860
So China has tended, they argue,
to specialize in rapid scale-up

00:48:06.860 --> 00:48:11.900
and cost reduction,
in combination.

00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:17.090
And they join really
remarkable skills

00:48:17.090 --> 00:48:21.980
in simultaneous management
of the tempo of production

00:48:21.980 --> 00:48:26.450
and production volume
and controlling cost,

00:48:26.450 --> 00:48:32.990
and that that's a very powerful
set of skills and capabilities,

00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:36.860
and that these kinds of factors
are much better explanations

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:42.950
for that remarkable rise than
simply a wage differential.

00:48:42.950 --> 00:48:45.950
So they argue that this has
enabled China to expand even

00:48:45.950 --> 00:48:48.290
in industries that are
highly automated or not

00:48:48.290 --> 00:48:52.280
on governmental priority lists.

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:54.740
And low costs and
government support

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:58.040
are just not
sufficient to explain

00:48:58.040 --> 00:49:00.230
China's remarkable
accomplishments

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:01.350
in manufacturing.

00:49:01.350 --> 00:49:04.340
So let's get more into
a little detail here.

00:49:04.340 --> 00:49:08.480
China's developing
production processes

00:49:08.480 --> 00:49:10.490
in areas that were
previously thought

00:49:10.490 --> 00:49:14.780
fully mature and impervious
to additional cost reductions

00:49:14.780 --> 00:49:16.580
or technological improvement.

00:49:16.580 --> 00:49:20.180
China's taken on various sectors
and shown that, in fact, you

00:49:20.180 --> 00:49:25.010
can bring innovation to
these in process and in cost.

00:49:25.010 --> 00:49:30.770
So the key has been accumulation
of firm-specific expertise

00:49:30.770 --> 00:49:34.040
that has enabled what they call
"extensive, multidirectional,

00:49:34.040 --> 00:49:35.310
inter-firm learning."

00:49:35.310 --> 00:49:41.210
In other words, they're able
to get a community of producers

00:49:41.210 --> 00:49:45.230
to operate together in a
unified kind of way that's

00:49:45.230 --> 00:49:47.570
kind of unthinkable in
the much more fragmented,

00:49:47.570 --> 00:49:49.985
decentralized US system--

00:49:49.985 --> 00:49:51.860
to build a level of
cooperation, particularly

00:49:51.860 --> 00:49:55.670
in a regional basis, that is
able to scale up production

00:49:55.670 --> 00:50:01.990
very quickly in ways that
are pretty unprecedented.

00:50:01.990 --> 00:50:05.090
So elements of China's
new production model,

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:08.120
they argue, include
backward design capability--

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:10.520
in other words, taking
an existing product

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:13.370
and rethinking it,
right, so that you

00:50:13.370 --> 00:50:21.120
can create lower cost production
systems for those components,

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:24.870
and therefore be able to sell
it into a lower cost, lower

00:50:24.870 --> 00:50:30.960
wage Chinese economy, right,
in a creative kind of way here.

00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:33.420
Yes, there's been a
partnership of foreign design

00:50:33.420 --> 00:50:34.860
and Chinese manufacturing.

00:50:34.860 --> 00:50:38.010
But that has been
multidirectional, they argue.

00:50:38.010 --> 00:50:40.650
Both sides have been
informing each other.

00:50:40.650 --> 00:50:43.620
And technology absorption
and collaborative development

00:50:43.620 --> 00:50:46.770
across networked production
firms has been remarkable.

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:49.950
That's part of this ability
to do rapid scale-up.

00:50:49.950 --> 00:50:55.090
So these are all new
elements that we haven't

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:59.380
seen in production systems, that
China's been able, they argue,

00:50:59.380 --> 00:51:01.390
to put together in unique ways.

00:51:01.390 --> 00:51:04.570
So an explanation of Chinese
manufacturing as just a wage

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:07.648
advantage completely
understates, they argue,

00:51:07.648 --> 00:51:09.440
what, in fact, China
has accomplished here.

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:11.470
It's a remarkable story.

00:51:11.470 --> 00:51:15.040
So we have to kind
of keep this in mind

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:18.700
as we confront these global
competitive issues in the class

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:19.600
today.

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:22.250
It's not a simple story
of a wage advantage.

00:51:22.250 --> 00:51:24.320
It's a much more complex
and interesting and

00:51:24.320 --> 00:51:28.243
innovation-based story.

00:51:28.243 --> 00:51:31.734
AUDIENCE: When we're putting
into detail about why China

00:51:31.734 --> 00:51:33.442
was so successful,
why it could do things

00:51:33.442 --> 00:51:37.246
in such a short time span, but
my question and the question

00:51:37.246 --> 00:51:41.420
some people have as
well was, what next,

00:51:41.420 --> 00:51:44.600
in terms of trade
relationships between--

00:51:44.600 --> 00:51:46.230
economic relationships
between the US--

