01:00:05.630 --> 01:00:07.470
But there's a thing called the
"innovator's dilemma," which is

01:00:07.470 --> 01:00:08.802
a common strategy in business.

01:00:08.802 --> 01:00:11.260
What you do, is you make the
product that isn't that great,

01:00:11.260 --> 01:00:12.758
but it's cheaper.

01:00:12.758 --> 01:00:14.800
And then what happens is
you do that specifically

01:00:14.800 --> 01:00:16.550
so your competitors
don't attack you.

01:00:16.550 --> 01:00:20.040
It's the equivalent of, say
you're at a dinner table

01:00:20.040 --> 01:00:21.540
and there's a person
who eats a lot.

01:00:21.540 --> 01:00:22.790
Right, he eats like 10 plates.

01:00:22.790 --> 01:00:25.420
And there's somebody who eats
like one little appetizer.

01:00:25.420 --> 01:00:26.710
You don't mind that
eating the appetizer.

01:00:26.710 --> 01:00:28.293
So they focus on
industries or markets

01:00:28.293 --> 01:00:30.130
that the big player
can't attack.

01:00:30.130 --> 01:00:32.130
And they slowly grow
their advantage.

01:00:32.130 --> 01:00:35.460
There's a strategy that was
used by Japanese companies

01:00:35.460 --> 01:00:37.220
with cars.

01:00:37.220 --> 01:00:39.477
They made the cheap car
that companies in the US

01:00:39.477 --> 01:00:41.310
wouldn't focus on until
they could make cars

01:00:41.310 --> 01:00:42.510
that were much, much better.

01:00:42.510 --> 01:00:44.058
But it's a common strategy.

