incentivized to do.

01:02:35.450 --> 01:02:38.610
So with that, if we
were to try to adopt

01:02:38.610 --> 01:02:40.510
that kind of a
structure, we'd have

01:02:40.510 --> 01:02:43.760
to make some radical
changes to the Constitution

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:47.660
and a lot of stuff.

01:02:47.660 --> 01:02:49.370
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah.

01:02:49.370 --> 01:02:51.620
It's hard for democracies
to think longer term.

01:02:51.620 --> 01:02:52.580
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:02:52.580 --> 01:02:53.830
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: All right.

01:02:53.830 --> 01:02:58.250
So we're going to dive
into Suzanne Berger's work

01:02:58.250 --> 01:03:00.830
on the "Production in the
Innovation Economy" study.

01:03:00.830 --> 01:03:03.530
So we talked last
class about her work

01:03:03.530 --> 01:03:05.540
on distributed production.

01:03:05.540 --> 01:03:10.250
And she led this big study
at MIT, the "PIE" study--

01:03:10.250 --> 01:03:12.680
"Production in the
Innovation Economy."

01:03:12.680 --> 01:03:16.940
Pulled together a whole faculty
group from a variety of fields

01:03:16.940 --> 01:03:23.030
and ended up with this
in-depth, two-volume study

01:03:23.030 --> 01:03:25.550
of what had been happening
in US production.

01:03:25.550 --> 01:03:29.870
And I think there's some
very important stories here.

01:03:29.870 --> 01:03:33.770
I had you read the kind
of preliminary report.

01:03:33.770 --> 01:03:37.650
The depth in the two volumes
is really quite powerful.

01:03:37.650 --> 01:03:40.370
So if you want to read
further in this area,

01:03:40.370 --> 01:03:41.780
this is a great place to start.

01:03:41.780 --> 01:03:46.160
So Suzanne wrote the kind
of cover, overall view,

01:03:46.160 --> 01:03:49.130
drawing on chapters that
particular faculty members

01:03:49.130 --> 01:03:52.625
and researchers pulled
together in different segments.

01:03:52.625 --> 01:03:54.500
And then she did that
kind of overview piece.

01:03:54.500 --> 01:03:57.950
The overview piece is one
of the most powerful books,

01:03:57.950 --> 01:04:01.610
in my view, that's been
written about US manufacturing.

01:04:01.610 --> 01:04:04.670
So well worth thinking about.

01:04:04.670 --> 01:04:07.550
You're just getting a
kind of early snapshot,

01:04:07.550 --> 01:04:11.390
frankly, from the preliminary
report I had you read.

01:04:11.390 --> 01:04:14.150
But I want to try and
pull out, frankly,

01:04:14.150 --> 01:04:16.700
blending the preliminary
report with my knowledge

01:04:16.700 --> 01:04:21.830
of the underlying
report some stories

01:04:21.830 --> 01:04:26.630
that I think help us
understand what's been going on

01:04:26.630 --> 01:04:29.720
in US manufacturing.

01:04:29.720 --> 01:04:34.220
And she tells a series
of these in her book.

01:04:34.220 --> 01:04:36.320
One story is that
manufacturing turns out

01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:37.910
not to be agriculture.

01:04:37.910 --> 01:04:40.160
And I'll explain
what in heaven's name

01:04:40.160 --> 01:04:43.040
I'm talking about in a minute.

01:04:43.040 --> 01:04:46.550
Secondly, that our manufacturing
firms are increasingly,

01:04:46.550 --> 01:04:50.660
as she puts it, "home alone,"
that small, mid-sized,

01:04:50.660 --> 01:04:53.180
and startup firms are
having a lot of trouble

01:04:53.180 --> 01:04:56.570
scaling up their
production in the US.

01:04:56.570 --> 01:05:01.610
A fourth story is about if you
want to keep strong innovation,

01:05:01.610 --> 01:05:03.770
you need to think about
the link between innovation

01:05:03.770 --> 01:05:08.900
and production, which this
book argues is profound--

01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:13.250
that there's a real link between
innovation and production.

01:05:13.250 --> 01:05:15.860
There's deep workforce
training education issues.

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:17.990
There's important
lessons from Germany.

01:05:17.990 --> 01:05:23.030
And then there's some very
interesting jobs stories here,

01:05:23.030 --> 01:05:24.053
too.

01:05:24.053 --> 01:05:25.595
So let me try and
tell these quickly.

01:05:28.990 --> 01:05:31.100
First, manufacturing
is not agriculture.

01:05:31.100 --> 01:05:36.530
For a long time, the economists
thought that manufacturing

01:05:36.530 --> 01:05:37.760
was agriculture.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:41.480
In other words, in 1900,
half the population--

01:05:41.480 --> 01:05:45.030
not quite-- but half the
population was farming.

01:05:45.030 --> 01:05:48.710
And now less than 2% of
the population is farming.

01:05:48.710 --> 01:05:51.710
And we're producing
much, much more, right.

01:05:51.710 --> 01:05:55.040
So it's a story of
staggering productivity gains

01:05:55.040 --> 01:05:56.630
and advances.

01:05:56.630 --> 01:05:59.780
But the MIT report takes
that argument apart.

01:05:59.780 --> 01:06:01.400
So economists were
saying, oh, this

01:06:01.400 --> 01:06:02.870
is just productivity gains.

01:06:02.870 --> 01:06:05.100
We're just much more
efficient in production.

01:06:05.100 --> 01:06:07.610
So what if you lost one
third of your manufacturing

01:06:07.610 --> 01:06:10.280
jobs between 2000 and 2010?

01:06:10.280 --> 01:06:11.180
No problem.

01:06:11.180 --> 01:06:13.400
Productivity gains, right.

01:06:13.400 --> 01:06:15.890
But then the story turns out
to be much more complicated.

01:06:19.620 --> 01:06:23.850
We thought that manufacturing
output was holding firm.

01:06:23.850 --> 01:06:27.780
But it turns out that
it wasn't, right.

01:06:27.780 --> 01:06:31.500
So we thought we were producing
the same with less labor.

01:06:31.500 --> 01:06:32.800
But it wasn't the case.

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:39.120
In fact, in 15 of 19 industrial
sectors, we had output decline.

01:06:39.120 --> 01:06:42.870
And our official statistics
overestimated output

01:06:42.870 --> 01:06:49.890
because we adopted a view of
computing and IT technologies

01:06:49.890 --> 01:06:55.030
that assumed the components,
for definitional reasons,

01:06:55.030 --> 01:06:56.515
were because the United States.

01:06:56.515 --> 01:06:58.030
But they weren't, right.

01:06:58.030 --> 01:07:02.500
That's the Willy Shih,
Gary Pisano story, right.

01:07:02.500 --> 01:07:05.560
So we were completely
inflating our numbers.

01:07:05.560 --> 01:07:07.720
And output wasn't what
we thought it was.

01:07:10.360 --> 01:07:14.890
So if output, which is obviously
half the story of productivity,

01:07:14.890 --> 01:07:18.160
is not what you thought it was,
then the productivity numbers

01:07:18.160 --> 01:07:21.070
were considerably lower
than mainstream economics

01:07:21.070 --> 01:07:22.063
had been telling us.

01:07:22.063 --> 01:07:23.980
It's not that there
weren't productivity gains

01:07:23.980 --> 01:07:25.040
in that period.

01:07:25.040 --> 01:07:26.140
There were.

01:07:26.140 --> 01:07:28.240
But they weren't what
we thought they were.

01:07:28.240 --> 01:07:31.810
So instead, the job loss
numbers really tells us

01:07:31.810 --> 01:07:38.170
the sector is hollowing out,
not getting more productive.

01:07:38.170 --> 01:07:42.070
So a second story--

01:07:42.070 --> 01:07:45.080
what Suzanne calls the
"home alone" story.

01:07:45.080 --> 01:07:49.190
So she tells a story that,
for the last several decades,

01:07:49.190 --> 01:07:52.930
we've been thinning out in the
US our manufacturing sector.

01:07:52.930 --> 01:07:55.930
We used to have firms
and supply chains that

01:07:55.930 --> 01:07:58.070
had to be very
vertically integrated.

01:07:58.070 --> 01:08:01.870
This is the story we told last
week about LEGOs and model

01:08:01.870 --> 01:08:04.180
airplanes, right.

01:08:04.180 --> 01:08:06.970
We hit on a financial model.

01:08:06.970 --> 01:08:09.280
And Martin, you had been
pointing some of this out.

01:08:09.280 --> 01:08:13.300
We hit on a financial model that
emphasized quarterly returns,

01:08:13.300 --> 01:08:18.430
which led us to want to reduce
interim risk, which led us

01:08:18.430 --> 01:08:21.729
in the financial sector
to focus on getting firms

01:08:21.729 --> 01:08:24.819
to nurture their
core competency,

01:08:24.819 --> 01:08:27.010
not do a lot of other stuff.

01:08:27.010 --> 01:08:31.850
So therefore, they should go
what's called "asset light."

01:08:31.850 --> 01:08:34.840
Strip the firm of
assets that are not

01:08:34.840 --> 01:08:36.800
part of its core competency.

01:08:36.800 --> 01:08:37.300
Right.

01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:41.830
So we began to thin out what
had been these very vertically

01:08:41.830 --> 01:08:46.149
integrated groups of firms.

01:08:46.149 --> 01:08:52.859
So the companies in the system
are now much more "home alone."

01:08:52.859 --> 01:08:55.770
Story number 3 is related.

01:08:55.770 --> 01:08:58.109
This is the scale-up problem.

01:08:58.109 --> 01:09:02.250
So the US is home to
a large percentage

01:09:02.250 --> 01:09:04.140
of the world's multinationals.

01:09:04.140 --> 01:09:05.069
They're global.

01:09:05.069 --> 01:09:06.779
They can get
production efficiencies

01:09:06.779 --> 01:09:09.540
by producing in
lower-cost countries.

01:09:09.540 --> 01:09:11.558
And they need to be
in global markets.

01:09:11.558 --> 01:09:12.850
They don't have an option here.

01:09:12.850 --> 01:09:15.990
They need to be worldwide.

01:09:15.990 --> 01:09:18.930
Generally speaking, they're OK.

01:09:18.930 --> 01:09:22.229
They're producing more abroad
than they did in the past.

01:09:22.229 --> 01:09:24.870
But there's two much
more vulnerable sectors.

01:09:24.870 --> 01:09:28.079
So one of those sectors
are what we could call,

01:09:28.079 --> 01:09:31.529
and what the book calls,
"Main Street firms."

01:09:31.529 --> 01:09:36.000
So these are the small
and mid-sized firms.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:40.620
So there are between 250,000
and 300,000-- let's call

01:09:40.620 --> 01:09:42.960
the 250,000 of these
small and mid-sized firms

01:09:42.960 --> 01:09:45.569
that employ less
than 500 people.

01:09:45.569 --> 01:09:47.760
That is most of the
manufacturing sector, that's

01:09:47.760 --> 01:09:51.090
a majority of US production.

01:09:51.090 --> 01:09:54.510
They have trouble
getting scale-up funding.

01:09:54.510 --> 01:09:56.970
They are thinly capitalized.

01:09:56.970 --> 01:10:00.330
They have to be risk
averse to survive.

01:10:00.330 --> 01:10:06.400
They don't do what we would
consider R&D, although they

01:10:06.400 --> 01:10:10.330
can be very innovative in
modifying products and changing

01:10:10.330 --> 01:10:11.150
processes.

01:10:11.150 --> 01:10:13.930
But they don't do
what we would consider

01:10:13.930 --> 01:10:17.110
innovation-based research.

01:10:17.110 --> 01:10:23.920
So they're kind of outside
of the US innovation system.

01:10:23.920 --> 01:10:25.870
And there are a lot of them.

01:10:25.870 --> 01:10:28.000
It's a big part of this.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:29.650
For them to innovate,
they have to have

01:10:29.650 --> 01:10:33.330
access to ideas, which they
don't necessarily have,

01:10:33.330 --> 01:10:35.740
and a thinned-out ecosystem.

01:10:35.740 --> 01:10:39.370
And they've got to have
the financing to scale up.

01:10:39.370 --> 01:10:42.430
Part of the Production in
the Innovation Economy study

01:10:42.430 --> 01:10:48.100
was led by John Reed, who
was head of the MIT Executive

01:10:48.100 --> 01:10:50.360
Committee and former
chairman of Citicorp--

01:10:50.360 --> 01:10:53.620
a brilliant, famous
banker, who created

01:10:53.620 --> 01:10:56.830
a lot of the amazing
Citicorp model.

01:10:56.830 --> 01:10:59.170
John Reed was part of
these deliberations.

01:10:59.170 --> 01:11:05.410
And he said, yes, we ended local
banking in the United States.

01:11:05.410 --> 01:11:09.040
That was the historic era where
your neighborhood banker would

01:11:09.040 --> 01:11:15.340
know, in your city or town,
who the quality producers were

01:11:15.340 --> 01:11:17.380
and know who to lend to.

01:11:17.380 --> 01:11:18.460
That's gone.

01:11:18.460 --> 01:11:23.170
We substituted really
national and then

01:11:23.170 --> 01:11:25.330
international financing models.

01:11:25.330 --> 01:11:28.660
And we replaced that
face-to-face, kind

01:11:28.660 --> 01:11:34.090
of relationship-based banking
to a very significant extent.

01:11:34.090 --> 01:11:35.830
The Main Street firms
were dramatically

01:11:35.830 --> 01:11:39.400
affected by their ability
to get scale-up money out

01:11:39.400 --> 01:11:40.670
of their banking system.

01:11:40.670 --> 01:11:42.835
Right, it really hit them.

01:11:42.835 --> 01:11:44.710
And there isn't really
a substitute for them.

01:11:44.710 --> 01:11:47.085
And then meanwhile-- and we'll
talk about this more later

01:11:47.085 --> 01:11:49.240
in class--

01:11:49.240 --> 01:11:51.010
the other
manufacturing community

01:11:51.010 --> 01:11:53.560
is entrepreneurial
startups that want

01:11:53.560 --> 01:11:55.930
to make something-- that want
to make a hard technology.

01:11:58.710 --> 01:12:01.020
Unfortunately, the
venture capital system

01:12:01.020 --> 01:12:04.700
has walked from this territory.

01:12:04.700 --> 01:12:08.360
So venture capital at this point
in the US funds predominantly

01:12:08.360 --> 01:12:11.180
software, secondarily
biotech, then

01:12:11.180 --> 01:12:13.940
a series of service sectors like
media entertainment business

01:12:13.940 --> 01:12:16.490
services.

01:12:16.490 --> 01:12:20.060
They're not funding firms
that want to make something,

01:12:20.060 --> 01:12:22.430
that have hard technologies.

01:12:22.430 --> 01:12:26.127
So the implications of this
are really quite powerful.

01:12:26.127 --> 01:12:28.460
That's part of the reason why
Rafael Reif put The Engine

01:12:28.460 --> 01:12:30.560
together down the
street, because a lot

01:12:30.560 --> 01:12:34.900
of MIT-developed hard technology
was just not getting out.

01:12:34.900 --> 01:12:37.670
We had to have a different
way to stand them up.

01:12:37.670 --> 01:12:40.810
But this is where the next
generation of manufacturing

01:12:40.810 --> 01:12:41.540
will come from.

01:12:41.540 --> 01:12:43.790
This is what the next
generation of manufactured goods

01:12:43.790 --> 01:12:45.230
will come from.

01:12:45.230 --> 01:12:47.080
And we're not doing it.

01:12:47.080 --> 01:12:47.760
Right.

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:51.900
Big-time societal
implications here.

01:12:51.900 --> 01:12:57.995
So there's a big scale-up
problem for these two, right.

01:12:57.995 --> 01:13:00.120
How are you going to scale
up innovative production

01:13:00.120 --> 01:13:01.982
and innovative technologies?

01:13:01.982 --> 01:13:03.940
We're in trouble to the
extent we rely on them.

01:13:03.940 --> 01:13:06.530
We rely on them a lot.

01:13:06.530 --> 01:13:10.470
This is just a chart that
shows who does the R&D.

01:13:10.470 --> 01:13:15.330
So large companies do R&D.
Small companies don't.

01:13:15.330 --> 01:13:15.830
Right.

01:13:15.830 --> 01:13:17.288
So the small
companies are just not

01:13:17.288 --> 01:13:18.590
part of the innovation system.

01:13:22.260 --> 01:13:25.440
Story 4-- the relationship
between innovation

01:13:25.440 --> 01:13:27.330
and production.

01:13:27.330 --> 01:13:31.260
So what's wrong with
scaling up abroad?

01:13:35.705 --> 01:13:38.780
The issue is that for most
products-- not all products--

01:13:38.780 --> 01:13:42.050
and it looks like there's a lot
of exceptions in the IT area--

01:13:42.050 --> 01:13:44.180
but for most products,
you need your innovation

01:13:44.180 --> 01:13:46.820
pretty closely
related, particularly

01:13:46.820 --> 01:13:48.950
to your initial
production stage.

01:13:48.950 --> 01:13:53.030
In other words, there's
a lot of interchange

01:13:53.030 --> 01:13:54.320
as you design for production.

01:13:54.320 --> 01:13:56.740
You take your idea, and you
design it for production.

01:13:56.740 --> 01:13:57.768
Right.

01:13:57.768 --> 01:13:59.060
That's a very creative process.

01:13:59.060 --> 01:14:00.860
Lots of engineering.

01:14:00.860 --> 01:14:04.400
You often have to rethink
your basic science.

01:14:04.400 --> 01:14:08.875
So if you're shifting your
production capability abroad--

01:14:08.875 --> 01:14:13.850
and this is the most important
conclusion of the PIE study--

01:14:13.850 --> 01:14:16.280
you're starting to affect
your innovation capability.

01:14:16.280 --> 01:14:20.440
So the US has thought that its
competitive advantage, really

01:14:20.440 --> 01:14:24.340
since the end of World War
II, is in a strong innovation

01:14:24.340 --> 01:14:25.550
system.

01:14:25.550 --> 01:14:27.640
But if it's shifting
production--

01:14:27.640 --> 01:14:30.370
particularly
initial production--

01:14:30.370 --> 01:14:35.470
it's losing that interaction
between initial production

01:14:35.470 --> 01:14:39.460
and its innovation capability.

01:14:39.460 --> 01:14:43.570
So a fifth story
is, how do you begin

01:14:43.570 --> 01:14:44.890
to wrestle with these issues?

01:14:44.890 --> 01:14:47.480
They looked hard at workforce.

01:14:47.480 --> 01:14:50.470
So there's lots of
workforce studies out.

01:14:50.470 --> 01:14:52.240
And they consist
of CEOs saying, we

01:14:52.240 --> 01:14:55.310
don't have enough
skilled workers.

01:14:55.310 --> 01:15:01.740
And the MIT approach, led
by Paul Osterman, a faculty

01:15:01.740 --> 01:15:07.890
member at Sloan, said, look,
let's not ask the CEOs, right.

01:15:07.890 --> 01:15:12.670
The CEOs may be saying
there's a tremendous shortage

01:15:12.670 --> 01:15:16.030
of $10,000 Cadillacs, right.

01:15:16.030 --> 01:15:18.307
That may be what they're,
in effect, saying.

01:15:18.307 --> 01:15:20.140
In other words, what
they're prepared to pay

01:15:20.140 --> 01:15:23.995
for skills is not an appropriate
compensation for the skills.

01:15:23.995 --> 01:15:25.660
It doesn't match markets.

01:15:25.660 --> 01:15:29.560
So let's actually ask the
human resources departments.

01:15:29.560 --> 01:15:32.050
And let's not ask them, are
you short of skilled workers?

01:15:32.050 --> 01:15:35.260
Let's ask them, how
long did it take

01:15:35.260 --> 01:15:39.430
you to hire for positions that
have come up in your firm?

01:15:39.430 --> 01:15:43.660
And what they found was that
75% of the firms studied--

01:15:43.660 --> 01:15:45.740
and they reached
way over 1,000--

01:15:45.740 --> 01:15:47.530
I think was several thousand--

01:15:47.530 --> 01:15:51.170
they were able to
hire within one month.

01:15:51.170 --> 01:15:52.190
Now, that's logical.

01:15:52.190 --> 01:15:55.400
Because, after all, we just laid
off almost 6 million production

01:15:55.400 --> 01:15:57.310
workers, right.

01:15:57.310 --> 01:15:59.830
And they've been largely shunted
into the lower end service

01:15:59.830 --> 01:16:01.012
sectors.

01:16:01.012 --> 01:16:02.470
Maybe they would
want to come back.

01:16:02.470 --> 01:16:07.150
So presumably, there's a
surplus of capability out there.

01:16:07.150 --> 01:16:14.760
But the most interesting
part of what they found

01:16:14.760 --> 01:16:18.210
was that for 25% of
the firms, they weren't

01:16:18.210 --> 01:16:20.010
able to hire in a month.

01:16:20.010 --> 01:16:21.780
It was taking them a lot longer.

01:16:21.780 --> 01:16:25.620
And interestingly, these
tended to be the smaller,

01:16:25.620 --> 01:16:32.550
more innovative,
technology-focused firms.

01:16:32.550 --> 01:16:34.710
And they were having a
much harder time, actually,

01:16:34.710 --> 01:16:37.530
because they needed a higher
skill raft of workers.

01:16:37.530 --> 01:16:41.220
They are having a lot of trouble
hiring in a reasonable time

01:16:41.220 --> 01:16:42.180
frame.

01:16:42.180 --> 01:16:45.930
So Paul Osterman would
summarize saying,

01:16:45.930 --> 01:16:47.670
there's not an
immediate emergency here

01:16:47.670 --> 01:16:49.470
on workforce skills.

01:16:49.470 --> 01:16:51.210
But we're going to
have trouble ahead.

01:16:51.210 --> 01:16:56.970
And the signal is the 25%
of more innovative firms

01:16:56.970 --> 01:16:59.310
that are having more trouble
getting the skill sets

01:16:59.310 --> 01:17:01.170
that they needed.

01:17:01.170 --> 01:17:04.260
And look, we've got a
big demographics problem.

01:17:04.260 --> 01:17:08.200
So the manufacturing workforce
is an aging workforce.

01:17:08.200 --> 01:17:11.860
And it's going to
need replacing.

01:17:11.860 --> 01:17:14.620
Sixth story-- and there's only
one more to go after this--

01:17:14.620 --> 01:17:17.720
what can we learn from Germany?

01:17:17.720 --> 01:17:20.980
So the US has been sitting
around for at least a decade--

01:17:20.980 --> 01:17:22.390
more like 20 years--

01:17:22.390 --> 01:17:27.650
thinking, oh, we have to
lose manufacturing jobs,

01:17:27.650 --> 01:17:29.840
because we're high
wage and high cost.

01:17:29.840 --> 01:17:32.330
So we have to lose these jobs.

01:17:32.330 --> 01:17:35.360
Somebody never sent
that memo to Germany.

01:17:35.360 --> 01:17:37.820
They failed to get
that word, right.

01:17:37.820 --> 01:17:39.983
Because Germany is much
higher wage and higher

01:17:39.983 --> 01:17:41.150
cost than the United States.

01:17:41.150 --> 01:17:45.080
Their wages and benefits are 66%
higher for their manufacturing

01:17:45.080 --> 01:17:48.050
workers than for US
manufacturing workers.

01:17:48.050 --> 01:17:51.950
And they are running staggering
trade surpluses with everybody,

01:17:51.950 --> 01:17:54.590
including a major trade
surplus with Germany--

01:17:54.590 --> 01:17:56.960
I mean with China, excuse me.

01:17:56.960 --> 01:17:58.280
What are they doing?

01:17:58.280 --> 01:18:00.140
They're supposed to
lose this sector,

01:18:00.140 --> 01:18:01.880
right, according
to our thinking.

01:18:01.880 --> 01:18:03.420
But they didn't.

01:18:03.420 --> 01:18:08.000
So the US has about 8% of its
workforce in production jobs.

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:10.860
Germany, 20%.

01:18:10.860 --> 01:18:12.390
What are they doing?

01:18:12.390 --> 01:18:13.230
Right.

01:18:13.230 --> 01:18:17.340
This is an important
set of lessons here.

01:18:17.340 --> 01:18:20.640
How has Germany organized
its manufacturing sector

01:18:20.640 --> 01:18:25.260
so that it's able to run
an extremely successful

01:18:25.260 --> 01:18:26.850
manufacturing sector
that continues

01:18:26.850 --> 01:18:29.883
to bring major returns
back to its economy,

01:18:29.883 --> 01:18:31.800
even though it's very
high wage and high cost?

01:18:31.800 --> 01:18:33.100
What are they doing?

01:18:33.100 --> 01:18:34.230
Right.

01:18:34.230 --> 01:18:40.020
So there may be important
lessons for us to learn.

01:18:40.020 --> 01:18:43.680
And the PIE study, in fact,
went through a number of these.

01:18:43.680 --> 01:18:48.400
They found that, unlike the
US, which was thinning out its

01:18:48.400 --> 01:18:52.470
ecosystem for its manufacturers,
that its small and mid-sized

01:18:52.470 --> 01:18:55.110
manufacturers, in particular,
were more "home alone,"

01:18:55.110 --> 01:18:57.330
Germany was doing the opposite--

01:18:57.330 --> 01:19:00.190
a much more connected,
collaborative system,

01:19:00.190 --> 01:19:04.317
right-- in part through a
Fraunhofer network system that,

01:19:04.317 --> 01:19:06.900
starting at the end of World War
II and partially, by the way,

01:19:06.900 --> 01:19:10.140
paid for by the
Marshall Plan by the US,

01:19:10.140 --> 01:19:13.242
brought large and small
and mid-sized firms.

01:19:13.242 --> 01:19:14.950
In Germany, the small
and mid-sized firms

01:19:14.950 --> 01:19:16.440
are called Mittelstand.

01:19:16.440 --> 01:19:20.010
And it's a famous German
capability, these very talented

01:19:20.010 --> 01:19:22.490
small and mid-sized firms.

01:19:22.490 --> 01:19:24.150
They were able to
bring them together

01:19:24.150 --> 01:19:29.460
in collaborations around new
innovations in production.

01:19:29.460 --> 01:19:33.480
And they would work together,
assisted by German engineering

01:19:33.480 --> 01:19:35.880
academics in the process.

01:19:35.880 --> 01:19:40.170
They have 60 of these
Fraunhofer institutes,

01:19:40.170 --> 01:19:44.130
really manufacturing institutes,
spread all over the country.

01:19:44.130 --> 01:19:48.450
So they have a way of avoiding
the "home alone" problem.

01:19:48.450 --> 01:19:50.220
If anything, they're
ever enriching

01:19:50.220 --> 01:19:52.080
the collaboration
between their firms

01:19:52.080 --> 01:19:53.205
and the trade-off of ideas.

01:19:55.830 --> 01:20:00.945
They have a whole system
for collaborative R&D

01:20:00.945 --> 01:20:03.070
that's shared between the
small and mid-sized firms

01:20:03.070 --> 01:20:04.420
and the larger firms.

01:20:04.420 --> 01:20:08.560
Through that system, they
have the most famous workforce

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:10.480
training system in
the world, through

01:20:10.480 --> 01:20:12.700
a remarkable
apprenticeship system

01:20:12.700 --> 01:20:15.520
that consistently
produces incredibly highly

01:20:15.520 --> 01:20:17.980
skilled workers.

01:20:17.980 --> 01:20:19.450
And the apprenticeships
will last

01:20:19.450 --> 01:20:21.910
for three or four years, right.

01:20:21.910 --> 01:20:23.437
Really in-depth training.

01:20:23.437 --> 01:20:24.520
We have nothing like that.

01:20:24.520 --> 01:20:26.660
We have highly
decentralized labor markets

01:20:26.660 --> 01:20:27.610
in the United States.

01:20:27.610 --> 01:20:30.370
We have nothing close to this.

01:20:30.370 --> 01:20:32.050
So they have a whole
shared training

01:20:32.050 --> 01:20:34.540
system for their workforce.

01:20:34.540 --> 01:20:36.850
And they've developed
ways through

01:20:36.850 --> 01:20:39.280
these collaborative
mechanisms to rapidly scale up

01:20:39.280 --> 01:20:40.630
their production.

01:20:40.630 --> 01:20:47.720
So Germany's workforce in
manufacturing is 80% unionized.

01:20:47.720 --> 01:20:50.170
We're not remotely
close to that.

01:20:50.170 --> 01:20:51.695
It's a different system.

01:20:51.695 --> 01:20:54.070
It's hard for the US to do an
apprenticeship system here.

01:20:54.070 --> 01:20:57.370
It doesn't quite match the
way we organize things.

01:20:57.370 --> 01:21:02.260
But there are some ideas
that we could learn from.

01:21:02.260 --> 01:21:06.170
And the seventh and last
story is about jobs.

01:21:06.170 --> 01:21:12.340
The manufacturing sector
affects our services sector.

01:21:15.500 --> 01:21:21.220
And Suzanne Berger and the team
tell an interesting story here,

01:21:21.220 --> 01:21:25.470
that the 21st
century firm, right,

01:21:25.470 --> 01:21:30.390
is going to increasingly
tie a complex hard product

01:21:30.390 --> 01:21:34.650
to a service and link
them, and offer customers

01:21:34.650 --> 01:21:38.880
solutions-- not a
good or a service,

01:21:38.880 --> 01:21:41.050
but a solution to a problem.

01:21:41.050 --> 01:21:44.310
So your Apple
iPhone, in many ways,

01:21:44.310 --> 01:21:49.410
is a combined service delivery
hardware technology, right.

01:21:49.410 --> 01:21:52.130
There's lots of service delivery
through that Apple iPhone,

01:21:52.130 --> 01:21:53.280
right.

01:21:53.280 --> 01:21:57.630
Things are going to be more
like that in the future.

01:21:57.630 --> 01:22:03.660
Now, personal services
tend to be face-to-face.

01:22:03.660 --> 01:22:08.020
And they're hard to
scale up quickly, right.

01:22:08.020 --> 01:22:10.240
It's their kind of one-to-one
relationship building.

01:22:10.240 --> 01:22:12.940
And that process
takes a long time.

01:22:12.940 --> 01:22:16.000
Whereas if you're producing
a manufactured good,

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:19.550
you can produce one
product on day 1.

01:22:19.550 --> 01:22:22.760
On day 12, you can produce
a million products, right.

01:22:22.760 --> 01:22:24.190
You can scale very quickly--

01:22:24.190 --> 01:22:27.170
much faster than through a
personal service operation,

01:22:27.170 --> 01:22:27.670
right.

01:22:27.670 --> 01:22:29.980
So one advantage
of manufacturing

01:22:29.980 --> 01:22:33.220
is that it tends to scale
up the gains in your economy

01:22:33.220 --> 01:22:34.997
much more quickly.

01:22:34.997 --> 01:22:36.580
Part of the reason
why it took so long

01:22:36.580 --> 01:22:40.570
to recover from the
2007, 2008 recession

01:22:40.570 --> 01:22:43.450
is that we had so damaged
our manufacturing sector

01:22:43.450 --> 01:22:47.140
that the normal scale-up
coming out of a recession just

01:22:47.140 --> 01:22:47.860
wasn't happening.

01:22:47.860 --> 01:22:48.777
It was taking forever.

01:22:52.150 --> 01:22:56.820
But if you're able to combine
a tradable good, right, that

01:22:56.820 --> 01:23:03.600
can scale with a
service, then the service

01:23:03.600 --> 01:23:07.710
starts to become
tradable as well, right--

01:23:07.710 --> 01:23:09.780
and can scale.

01:23:09.780 --> 01:23:11.850
So that's a whole new
capability in services

01:23:11.850 --> 01:23:14.670
that we haven't really spent
a lot of time thinking about.

01:23:14.670 --> 01:23:17.950
But it's very interesting,
since 86% of our workforce

01:23:17.950 --> 01:23:20.022
is in services.

01:23:20.022 --> 01:23:21.730
Maybe we ought to work
on this territory.

01:23:21.730 --> 01:23:24.870
But a prerequisite is
having the tradable goods

01:23:24.870 --> 01:23:28.020
that you can tie to
a service, right.

01:23:28.020 --> 01:23:32.220
Yet another reason why, in
the next generation of firms,

01:23:32.220 --> 01:23:37.300
manufacturing capability
is going to be important.

01:23:37.300 --> 01:23:38.800
You saw this chart before.

01:23:38.800 --> 01:23:43.590
This shows you where societal
returns come from, right.

01:23:43.590 --> 01:23:46.950
Predominantly from
production, not from services.

01:23:46.950 --> 01:23:49.410
So let me just summarize.

01:23:49.410 --> 01:23:53.550
Here's the stories that Suzanne
and the PIE study taught us.

01:23:53.550 --> 01:23:55.960
Manufacturing is
not agriculture.

01:23:55.960 --> 01:23:57.510
This sector was hollowing out.

01:23:57.510 --> 01:24:01.350
It wasn't enjoying productivity
advances to the extent

01:24:01.350 --> 01:24:02.620
we thought possible.

01:24:02.620 --> 01:24:05.190
Our manufacturing firms are
increasingly "home alone."

01:24:05.190 --> 01:24:08.160
Their ecosystems of
support are thinned out.

01:24:08.160 --> 01:24:12.690
There's less of what Pisano
and Shih called a "commons"

01:24:12.690 --> 01:24:14.610
available to support them.

01:24:14.610 --> 01:24:17.895
There's a real scale-up problem
for small, mid-sized firms,

01:24:17.895 --> 01:24:20.145
and for startup firms, for
somewhat different reasons.

01:24:22.970 --> 01:24:26.640
There's important linkage
between innovation

01:24:26.640 --> 01:24:28.120
and production.

01:24:28.120 --> 01:24:30.340
These are very related
and tied to each other.

01:24:30.340 --> 01:24:34.680
And if you lose one,
it'll affect the other.

01:24:34.680 --> 01:24:38.250
There's interesting
lessons about workforce,

01:24:38.250 --> 01:24:40.850
that we've got a problem ahead
in up-scaling our workforce.

01:24:40.850 --> 01:24:42.600
It's not an emergency
now, but we probably

01:24:42.600 --> 01:24:44.550
have a problem ahead.

01:24:44.550 --> 01:24:46.840
Very important
lessons from Germany

01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:50.760
on the societal benefits of
a strong production sector.

01:24:50.760 --> 01:24:53.070
And then, in this
jobs area, if you're

01:24:53.070 --> 01:24:57.330
able to tie tradable
goods to services,

01:24:57.330 --> 01:25:00.780
then the services themselves
become tradable and scalable,

01:25:00.780 --> 01:25:02.290
as well.

01:25:02.290 --> 01:25:05.680
And then, there's an
underlying question

01:25:05.680 --> 01:25:08.020
about how our manufacturing
sector, therefore,

01:25:08.020 --> 01:25:10.700
affects our services sector.

01:25:10.700 --> 01:25:13.263
So let's come back and do
some questions about this.

01:25:13.263 --> 01:25:15.430
And then we'll dive into
the next round of readings.

01:25:15.430 --> 01:25:17.970
And Steph will lead us in those.